What is an Outdial?
-------------------

        An OutDial modem is simply a Modem connected to a computer system
  used for the purpose of dialng out.  There a two types of OutDials: Local,
  and Global.  Local OutDials will only call numbers that are local to the
  modems phone line,  ie. it will not call 1-xxx-xxx-xxxx numbers.  If you
  attempt to dial a 1- number on a Local modem it will usually return a
  BUSY code.  This is because the modem hears the "doo doo doo I am sorry
  the number you have reached blah blah blah" and thinks its a busy signal.
  A Global OutDial will call any phone number that can be called direct.  The
  best way to test if a OutDial is Local or Global is to call a long distance
  telenet port <or anything that you know will not be busy>.  If it connects
  its a Global.  If its busy it probably a Local.

How to Use an Outdial.
----------------------

    Oudials are very easy to use.  If you know how to use your own modem
    you can use an outdial.  Just give it an AT command like this..

         atdtxxxxxxx   where the x's are the phone number.

    Some outdials won't put you in terminal mode..  The only one that I have
    used that doesn't put you in terminal mode is one that prompts with a !
    With these you just do this...

         !dxxxxxxx   again where the x's are the phone number

    Some outdials have just a regular ole user friendly menu..  so just read
    the menus and the help screens.

note-

      change the parity of your terminal program after connecting with
      the outdial in order to call systems with no parity.
